  "summary": "After leaving the hall of the Inoue mansion, Xuyan (Yuzu) asks the narrator, Mr. Kouyama, who \"Brutus\" is, a question the narrator perceives as destructive. As they walk along a path toward a lake, Yuzu questions the narrator's strange behavior in the hall. She claims his brother is \"already crazy\" and tells the story of Val Selan, a carpenter poisoned by his wife who became perceived as insane and lived in a state of delusion before being selected as a saint. Yuzu uses this allegory to discuss subjective truth and the nature of existence.\n\nWhen Wakamizu approaches, Yuzu leaves abruptly. The narrator asks if her comments referred to Selene or Shizuma, but receives no answer. The narrator then speaks with Mutsuzaki (Mukai), who observes that Yuzu is a clever woman. Mutsuzaki jokes about being manipulated by the murderer, suggesting there is an eight-eighth probability that a woman is the killer, though he quickly dismisses it as a joke to ease the narrator's unease.\n\nAs the narrator and Mutsuzaki return to the entrance gate, a piercing scream and the sound of Mahler's music signal a new tragedy. Inside, a dark brown box carved with scenes from the Kalevala, once cherished by Aku-ōn, is stained crimson with blood. The scene is described as a macabre parallel to Salome dancing with the severed head of John; Aku-ōn’s own severed head has been placed upon his prized box. Tsubaki and Kumiko observe the head of Akibas, noting that this new murder involves decapitation and adds new elements to the ongoing mystery.",
